726165f-a.title: Queens: Borden Avenue - 2nd Street
726165f-a.text:
Borden Avenue, east from 2nd Street. The first two-story
building on the left is an old street car barn; in the center
of the view is the 4-story Long Asland Railroad branch of the
Y.M.C.A.
P. L. Sperr  October 25, 1936

726166f-a.title: Queens: Borden Avenue - 2nd Street
726166f-a.text:
Borden Avenue, at, and adjoining the N.E. corner of
2nd Street. The corner building, which is now the 34th
Street Ferry Storage Warehouse, is the former Miller Hotel,
erected by Oliver Charlick, General Manager of the Long
Island Railroad, for Tony Miller (Mueller). It was a ren-
demvous for sportsmen. Richard Croker and Tim Sullivan
were guests here. The building was sold in 1917, altered,
and then used as a phonograph manufactory. It appears from
the photograph that the upper floor is used as living quafters;
a saloon occupies the ground floor on the right. The building
to the right is an old trolley barn, extending through to
51st Avenue.
P. L. Sperr  October 25, 1936
